Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco—On February 24, Russia's invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of a potential third world war that could destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping held a lengthy meeting on February 4—the day that marked the beginning of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
After the meeting, the two leaders released a meticulously drafted document of 5,000 words announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document was more powerful than any treaty and certainly required detailed negotiations in advance.
I am shocked that Xi seems to have fully entrusted Putin to invade and launch the war in Ukraine.
He believed that confirming his status as China's lifelong ruler in the second half of this year was merely a formality, and he was certainly confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his own hands, Xi meticulously planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin proceeded to realize his lifelong dream in an incredible brutal manner.
At nearly 70 years old, Putin feels that if he wants to leave a significant mark in Russian history, it has to be now or it will never happen.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar they can blindly follow.
This system is the exact opposite of a democratic society, and this vision distorts the "soul" of the emotionally sensitive Russian people to an extreme degree.
As a child, I had a lot of contact with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you asked them for a favor, they would share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I started what I call my political charity work.
At first, I established a foundation in my homeland Hungary, and later, I actively participated in activities that contributed to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this dissolution had already begun.
I also established foundations in Russia, and then in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I established a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (I closed this foundation in 1989, shortly before the massacre at Tiananmen Square erupted).
I personally do not know Putin, but I have closely followed his rise and fully understand his ruthless personality.
He reduced the capital of Chechnya, Grozny, to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB agent, but he seems to have changed recently.
He seems to have lost touch with reality because he has developed a fixed mindset.
Without a doubt, he miscalculated the situation in Ukraine.
He thought that Ukrainian speakers would open their arms to welcome Russian soldiers, but in fact, they were no different from the Ukrainian-speaking population.
Facing what seemed to be a one-sided possibility, the Ukrainian people still carried out an unbelievable courageous resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a lengthy article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that Ukrainians had been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
Since Kyiv was the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument was not without historical basis.
However, in the content of Part 2, it is Putin who was misled.
He should have known the facts much clearer.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely in the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The 2014 events made him very angry.
But when Russian troops were ordered to attack their Ukrainian brothers, they performed poorly.
The deeply rooted corruption in the Ministry of Defense when awarding contracts also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But instead of blaming himself, Putin seemed to have gone mad.
He was determined to punish Ukraine for opposing him, and his actions seemed to be unconstrained.
He threw the entire Russian army into battle and ignored all rules of engagement, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid supplying electricity to the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant (currently occupied by Russian forces) was also damaged.
In the besieged Mariupol, as many as 400,000 people have had no water or food for nearly a week.
Russia is very likely to lose this war.
The United States and the European Union are both sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, while also trying to purchase Russian-made MIG fighter jets operated by Ukrainian pilots.
These could change the entire situation.
No matter the outcome, Putin has already created a miracle in strengthening European determination and unity.
Meanwhile, Xi seemed to have become aware that Putin had gone astray.
On March 8, after China's Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that Sino-Russian friendship remained "as solid as a rock," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, expressing his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hoped for maximum restraint in the war.
Whether Putin would yield to Xi's wishes remained far from certain.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
